  <question type="stack">
    <name>
				<text>8.2.3.4 Exercise 3x3 linear system infinitely many solutions</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Consider the following linear system of equations: <span class="math display">\[\begin{matrix}
    {@eqq1@} \\
    {@eqq2@} \\
    {@eqq3@} \\
\end{matrix}\]</span>

</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">

    <li>
        <p> Consider the matrix form <span class="math inline">\(AX = B\)</span> of the system and identify <span class="math inline">\(A\)</span></p>
    </li>

    <div>\(A=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</div>
    <div><br></div>

    <li>
        <p>Find the determinant of <span class="math inline">\(A\)</span>: </p>
        <p><span class="math inline">\(|A| =\)</span> [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>Determine if the system has no solution, a unique solution, or infinitely many solutions.</p>
    </li>
    <p>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>

    <li>
        <p>If it has a unique solution or infinitely many solutions, these are:</p>
    </li>

    <p>\(x =\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] </p>

    <p>\(y =\) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] </p>

    <p>\(z =\) [[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] </p>

    <p> Give all the solutions if there is more than one. If there are no solutions, fill the gaps for \(x, y \) and \(z \) with the word <b>null</b>.</p>

</ol>
[[feedback:prt1]]]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
  <li>
<p> In matrix form \(AX = B\), the matrix \(A \) is \[ A = {@AA@}.\]</p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
<p> \( \det A = {@determinant(AA)@} \). </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
<p> Since the determinant of \(A \) is \( 0 \), we already know that the system has either no solution or infinitely many solutions. Note that if we consider the linear combination the first equation plus \({@kk@}\) times the second equation we get \[
    {@lhs(eqq1)@} + {@kk@} \cdot ({@lhs(eqq2)@}) = {@rhs(eqq1)@} + {@kk@} \cdot ({@rhs(eqq2)@}) \] which becomes \[ {@expand(lhs(eqq1) + kk * lhs(eqq2))@} = {@expand(rhs(eqq1) + kk * rhs(eqq2))@}.\] Note that this is the third equation. Therefore, the
    system has infinitely many solutions.</p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
<p> Since the third equation is a linear combination of the other two, we can ignore it. Setting \(z = t \), where \( t \) can be any real number, we can obtain all the solutions to the system with \( t \) as a parameter: \[ x = {@xx1@}, \qquad y = {@xx2@},
    \qquad z = {@xx3@}. \] You could also have chosen to set \(x = t \) (resp. \(y = t \)), and obtain equivalent expressions.</p>
  </li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
